'''HMAS ''Kuramia''''' was a [[Royal Australian Navy]] [[Net laying ship|boom defence vessel]], converted from a [[Sydney Ferries Limited]] ferry.
==History== ''Kuramia''' was built by [[David Drake Limited|David Drake]], [[Balmain, New South Wales|Balmain]] for [[Sydney Ferries Limited]], beng launched on 15 November 1913. Her triple expansion engines were built by [[Mort's Dock]], Balmain. She was operated on the [[Circular Quay ferry wharf|Circular Quay]] to [[Milsons Point ferry wharf|Milsons Point]] run. Made redundant by the opening of the [[Sydney Harbour Bridge]] in 1932, she was sold in 1940 and her machinery was removed. Part of her machinery was fitted in ''Uralba''. Her hull was requisitioned by the [[Royal Australian Navy]] in 1942 and she was converted to a [[Net laying ship|boom defence vessel]] for use at [[Sydney Heads]] until the end of [[World War II]].<ref name=FerriesofSydney>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160227125423/http://ferriesofsydney.com/kuramia.html SS Kuramia] Ferries of Sydney</ref>
==Fate== Her hulk was used as target by aircraft from [[HMAS Sydney (D48)|HMAS ''Sydney'']] off Sydney on 10 October 1953 and sunk.<ref name=FerriesofSydney/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/18392118 |title=Commonwealth of Australia, Emergency Notice to Mariners| publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 October 1953|page=13 |accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref>
